//correct program
#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>

int main()
{

    char a[]="Hello";
    char *p="Hai";

    strcpy(a,"Hai");   // copy into array
    p="Hello";         // reassign pointer

    printf("%s  %s\n",a,p);
}
//////////////////////////////////
🎓 One-Line Interview Answer

If interviewer shows this code, say:

This program will not compile because array names are not assignable.
We must use strcpy() to copy a new string into the array, while pointers can be reassigned directly.

🧠 Interview Concept Being Tested

This snippet checks whether you know:

✔ array name is not assignable
✔ pointer variable is assignable
✔ difference between copying string and assigning pointer
✔ string literal vs array storage

char *strcpy(char *dest, const char *src);
dest → where to copy
src → what to copy
returns pointer to dest

What strcpy Does Internally:
int i = 0;
while(src[i] != '\0')
{
    dest[i] = src[i];
    i++;
}
dest[i] = '\0';
